var definitions = ['<h2>Er mag sein brandneues Fahrrad.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". It indicates that the subject has a positive feeling towards something.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates that the following noun, "Fahrrad", belongs to him.</div><div><strong>brandneues</strong> This is a compound adjective in German made up of "brandneu", which means "brand new", and the ending "es", which is used here to agree with the neuter noun "Fahrrad". It describes the noun as being new and not previously used.</div><div><strong>Fahrrad</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "bicycle" or "bike". It is the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of being liked.</div>','<h2>Er ist für ein Kind sehr intelligent.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German which can mean "for", "to", or "because of", depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "for", introducing the reason or purpose.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It is used here before the noun "Kind".</div><div><strong>Kind</strong> This is a German noun meaning "child". In the sentence, it is in the accusative case following the preposition "für".</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It is used to intensify the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>intelligent</strong> This is an adjective that is the same in English and German, meaning "intelligent" or "smart". It is used here to describe the subject "Er" (he).</div>','<h2>Er ist der Vorsitzende der Firma.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>der Vorsitzende</strong> This is a noun phrase that means "the chairman" or "the president". "Der" is the masculine singular definitive article "the", and "Vorsitzende" is a masculine singular noun that denotes the person holding the position of chair or president of a company or organization.</div><div><strong>der Firma</strong> This is a genitive case noun phrase that means "of the company". "Der" here is the feminine singular genitive article "of the", indicating possession, and "Firma" is a feminine singular noun meaning "company". The genitive case is used in German to indicate possession, similar to "’s" or "of" in English.</div>','<h2>Sie fährt mit dem Bus zur Arbeit.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fährt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive" but in this context means "to travel" or "to go". It indicates the action the subject is taking.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German which translates to "with" in English. It is used here to describe the means of transportation.</div><div><strong>dem Bus</strong> "dem" is the dative definite article for masculine nouns and "Bus" is a masculine noun which means "bus". Combined, they mean "with the bus" in the context of this sentence, describing the mode of transportation she uses to get to work.</div><div><strong>zur Arbeit</strong> "zur" is a contraction of "zu der" in German, which translates to "to the" in English, where "zu" is a preposition meaning "to" and "der" is the definite article "the" in the feminine or plural dative case. "Arbeit" means "work". Together, "zur Arbeit" means "to work", indicating her destination.</div>','<h2>Sie spielt sehr gut Klavier.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun in the third-person singular feminine or the formal second-person singular or plural, equivalent to "she" or formal "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spielt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It indicates the action being carried out by the subject.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It’s used to enhance or emphasize the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is an adjective meaning "good" or "well" in English. In this context, it’s used as an adverb to describe the quality of the playing.</div><div><strong>Klavier</strong> This is a noun meaning "piano" in English. It indicates the instrument being played by the subject of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Sie ist eine wichtige Führungsperson im Staat.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being of the subject.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article in German for feminine and neuter nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>wichtige</strong> This is the feminine nominative form of the adjective "wichtig", which means "important". It agrees in gender, number, and case with the noun it describes.</div><div><strong>Führungsperson</strong> This is a compound noun in German, which can be broken down into "Führung" (leadership) and "Person" (person). Combined, it means "leading figure" or "leader". In this sentence, it is a feminine noun in the nominative singular case.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" and the definite article "dem", which together mean "in the" in English. "In" indicates the location or setting, and "dem" is the dative case of the masculine or neuter definite article.</div><div><strong>Staat</strong> This is the German noun for "state" or "country" in the masculine singular and is in the dative case following "im", influenced by the preposition "in" which requires the dative case when referring to a location.</div>','<h2>Wo ist das Auto? Es ist in der Garage.</h2><div><strong>Wo</strong> This is the German word for "where". It is used to ask for the location of an object or person.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject with its location.</div><div><strong>das Auto?</strong> This phrase means "the car" in English. "Das" is the neutral definite article "the", and "Auto" is the German word for "car". This is the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the neutral third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It refers back to "das Auto".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> As before, this is the third-person singular present tense form of "sein", here linking the subject with its location.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "in" or "into" in English, indicating the location of the subject.</div><div><strong>der Garage.</strong> This phrase means "the garage" in English. "Der" is the feminine definite article "the",, and "Garage" is the German word for "garage". Since "Garage" is feminine in German, the preposition "in" takes the form of "in der" to indicate the location where the car is.</div>','<h2>Das Buch ist blau. Es ist blau.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the neuter definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to specify the book being discussed.</div><div><strong>Buch</strong> This is a neuter noun in German meaning "book". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or the condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>blau</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "blue". It describes the color of the book and agrees in gender, number, and case with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the neuter third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It refers back to the book mentioned in the previous sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> As previously mentioned, this is the third-person singular present tense form of "sein", meaning "to be".</div><div><strong>blau (second occurrence)</strong> The adjective "blue" is repeated here to emphasize the color of the book once again.</div>','<h2>Es schneit.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>schneit</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "schneien", which means "to snow". It describes the action that is taking place, i.e., that snow is falling from the sky.</div>','<h2>Es macht viel Spaß, hier zu laufen.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>macht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "machen", which means "to make" or "to do". In this context, it translates to "makes" as in "it makes".</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is a German word meaning "much" or "a lot". It’s an indefinite pronoun that quantifies the amount of fun ("Spaß").</div><div><strong>Spaß</strong> This is a German noun meaning "fun". Here it is the direct object of the sentence, indicating what "it" makes a lot of.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is an adverb of place in German, meaning "here". It indicates the location where the fun activity is taking place.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a German infinitive marker. It appears before the verb "laufen" to form an infinitive phrase that functions as an adverbial phrase, explaining the activity that is fun.</div><div><strong>laufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "laufen", which means "to run" or "to walk" in German. In this sentence, it is part of the infinitive phrase "hier zu laufen" which means "to run here" or "to walk here".</div>','<h2>Es hat mir geschmeckt!</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It acts as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it’s part of the verb phrase "hat geschmeckt" which forms the perfect tense, used to describe a completed action.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "to me" or "for me" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the sentence – the person for whom the action of tasting was satisfactory.</div><div><strong>geschmeckt</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "schmecken", which means "to taste" or "to taste good". Combined with "hat", it completes the verb phrase, stating that "it has tasted [good]". The omission of "good" is implied and common in the German construction of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Es ist schwierig, auf das Eis zu klettern.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It often starts a sentence to express a general condition or situation.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state or condition of the subject.</div><div><strong>schwierig</strong> This is an adjective in German which translates to "difficult" in English. It describes the difficulty of the action that follows.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition which can mean "on" in English, indicating physical position or location.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the definite article in German for neuter nouns in the accusative case, which translates to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Eis</strong> This is the German word for "ice". It is a neuter noun, therefore partnered with "das" as the definite article in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>zu klettern</strong> This is an infinitive construction which combines "zu" (to) and "klettern" (to climb) in English. It indicates the purpose or the action being described as difficult.</div>','<h2>Wie spät ist es?</h2><div><strong>Wie</strong> This is the German word for "how". It is used to ask for the manner or degree of something, in this case regarding the time.</div><div><strong>spät</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "late". In the question, it refers to the progression of time—essentially inquiring about the hour of the day.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here as the main verb of the sentence.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neutral third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is used here as the subject of the sentence to refer to "the time".</div>','<h2>Es war zu kalt, um das Haus zu verlassen.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s often used as a dummy subject in sentences.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, it indicates the state or condition in the past.</div><div><strong>zu kalt</strong> This phrase combines "zu" (too) with "kalt" (cold), meaning "too cold". It describes the degree of coldness which is more than sufficient or necessary and acts as the reason for not doing something.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a conjunction often used with infinitive clauses, meaning "in order to" or "to", indicating the purpose or intent.</div><div><strong>das Haus</strong> This phrase means "the house". "Das" is the neutral definite article, and "Haus" is the noun for "house".</div><div><strong>zu verlassen</strong> This is an infinitive construction with "zu", which means "to" before a verb. "Verlassen" here means "to leave". This part of the sentence specifies what action is not being taken due to the coldness.</div>','<h2>Sie lernen viele interessante Sachen in der Schule.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" or the polite form of "you". In this sentence, it is the subject and either refers to a group of people learning or to a formal singular "you".</div><div><strong>lernen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the German verb "lernen", which means "to learn". If "Sie" is intended as the singular formal "you", "lernen" would still be used.</div><div><strong>viele</strong> This is a quantifier in German meaning "many". It is used here to indicate that a large number of things are being learned.</div><div><strong>interessante</strong> This is the plural form of the German adjective "interessant", meaning "interesting". In this sentence, it modifies "Sachen", hence it agrees with the plural and nominative case.</div><div><strong>Sachen</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Sache", meaning "things". It is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "lernen".</div><div><strong>in der Schule</strong> This phrase consists of the preposition "in", the definite article "der", and the noun "Schule", which means "school". "In der" indicates the location where the learning is taking place, which is "in the school". "Schule" is in the dative case here because "in" is a two-way preposition and it denotes a location where something is happening rather than a direction.</div>','<h2>Sie sind Studenten an der Universität.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English when capitalized. However, it can also act as the formal "you" when addressing someone directly, also capitalized. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It can also be used for the formal "you" as "are" in English. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>Studenten</strong> This is the plural form of "Student", a German noun meaning "students". It’s in the nominative case because it’s the subject complement that defines or identifies the subject "Sie".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition which can mean "on", "at", or "in" depending on its usage. In this context, it means "at" as it pertains to location.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the feminine singular definite article in the dative case in German, here meaning "the". The dative case is used following certain prepositions, including "an", when they denote a static location. "Universität" is feminine, so "der" is used.</div><div><strong>Universität</strong> This is a German noun meaning "university". It’s in the dative case here because it follows the preposition "an" which demands dative when describing a location where something is at.</div>','<h2>Sie beschlossen, mit dem Zug zu fahren.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" or the formal "you" when addressing someone with respect. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>beschlossen</strong> This is the past tense of the verb "beschließen", which means "to decide". In this sentence, it indicates that a decision was made.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition which means "with" when describing accompaniment or manner in which something is done.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English. In German, articles change form depending on the case, gender, and number. "Dem" is dative case and is used here because it follows the preposition "mit", which requires the dative case.</div><div><strong>Zug</strong> This is a German noun meaning "train". </div><div><strong>zu fahren</strong> This is an infinitive construction with "zu", which is often used after certain verbs or nouns, and in this case, it completes the meaning of the sentence "to travel by train". "Fahren" is the infinitive verb here meaning "to drive" or "to travel" (by vehicle).</div>','<h2>Sie wollten zu Hause einen Film schauen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. In formal address, it can also mean "you" as in the formal "you" for singular and plural, but the context of the sentence is required to determine the precise meaning.</div><div><strong>wollten</strong> This is the past tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want to". It indicates a past desire or intention.</div><div><strong>zu Hause</strong> This is a phrase meaning "at home". The preposition "zu" translates to "to" and "Hause" is a noun that can mean "house" or "home". The phrase "zu Hause" is used to refer to being in one’s own home.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular article "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun it modifies and indicates the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Film</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "film" or "movie" in English.</div><div><strong>schauen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb that means "to watch". In this sentence, it is combined with the modal verb "wollten" and means that the subject wanted to perform the action of watching.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Er ist nicht zu Hause.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German subject pronoun for "he". It’s the third-person singular pronoun and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicative expression.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb meaning "not" in English. It negates the statement to indicate that the subject is not in a particular state or place.</div><div><strong>zu Hause</strong> This phrase means "at home" in English. "Zu" can be translated as "to" or "at" and "Hause" is a dative form of "Haus", which means "house" or "home". Together, they describe the location or state of being of the subject.</div>','<h2>Er weiß es noch nicht.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun in the nominative case, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the subject has knowledge of something.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the German neuter pronoun in the accusative case, equivalent to "it" in English. Here, it’s used as the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>noch nicht</strong> This is a phrase made up of two words. "noch" translates to "still" or "yet", and "nicht" means "not". Combined, "noch nicht" expresses that something has not occurred yet, denoting the negative aspect "not yet" or "still not".</div>','<h2>Er kann sehr weit sehen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "to be able to". It indicates capability or possibility.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>weit</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "far". Here, it is used to describe the extent of the visibility - "far" in the sense of a long distance.</div><div><strong>sehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". In this sentence, it’s used to indicate the action of perceiving with the eyes, modified by "kann" to express ability.</div>','<h2>Er fährt viel zu schnell!</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fährt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is an adverb meaning "much" or "a lot". In this context, it intensifies the adverb that follows.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is an adverb usually meaning "too" in English. It is used here to indicate that the degree of speed is excessive.</div><div><strong>schnell!</strong> This is an adjective meaning "fast" or "quick". When used with "viel zu", it becomes "much too fast", indicating that someone is driving at an excessive speed.</div>','<h2>Er arbeitet morgen nicht.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>arbeitet</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "arbeiten", which means "to work". Here, it describes the action that the subject is engaged in, or rather in this case, not engaged in as indicated by the following word.</div><div><strong>morgen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "tomorrow". It indicates the time when the action of the verb is not going to take place.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates the verb of the sentence, thus indicating that the action (work) is not happening at the specified time (tomorrow).</div>','<h2>Er hat ein sehr gutes Gedächtnis.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or a state of being.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, used for masculine or neuter nouns in the nominative or accusative case. It translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It’s used to modify the adjective that follows and intensifies its meaning.</div><div><strong>gutes</strong> This is the accusative singular neuter form of the adjective "gut", which means "good". It describes the quality of the noun that follows, and agrees with the noun in gender, number, and case.</div><div><strong>Gedächtnis</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "memory" in English. It’s in the accusative case as it’s the direct object of the verb "haben".</div>','<h2>Er hat zwanzig Minuten gewartet.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>zwanzig Minuten</strong> Translates to "twenty minutes" in English. This phrase specifies the duration of time he was waiting.</div><div><strong>gewartet</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "warten", which means "to wait". In combination with "hat", it forms the perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div>','<h2>Er ist nicht so ängstlich wie ich.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes the state of being of the subject "Er".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It negates the adjective that follows or the entire statement depending on context.</div><div><strong>so</strong> This is an adverb in German which means "so" or "as" in English. It is used before an adjective or adverb to denote the degree or extent of something.</div><div><strong>ängstlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "anxious" or "fearful".</div><div><strong>wie</strong> This is a German comparative conjunction that means "as" or "like" in English. It is used to create a comparison between two things or persons.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is used here as the second entity in the comparison.</div>','<h2>Sie bezahlt für mich.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It can also be the formal "you" in singular or plural form. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bezahlt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "bezahlen", which means "to pay". It denotes the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>für</strong> This is a preposition in German meaning "for". It is used to indicate the beneficiary or the person on whose behalf the action is being taken.</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is the first-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It is the object of the preposition "für", indicating the person for whom the subject is paying.</div>','<h2>Sie fährt ein blaues Auto.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. This word is used as the subject of the sentence and refers to a female person.</div><div><strong>fährt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive". In this sentence, it describes the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun "Auto" and it’s in the accusative case due to the action of driving.</div><div><strong>blaues</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "blue". It describes the noun "Auto" and agrees in gender, case, and number with the noun it describes. In this instance, it is in the accusative case, masculine singular form due to its association with the noun "Auto".</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun in German, meaning "car". Here, it’s the direct object of the sentence, receiving the action of the verb "fahren". It is in the accusative case after the article "ein".</div>','<h2>Sie reist gerne allein.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, denoting the person who is performing the action.</div><div><strong>reist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "reisen", which means "to travel". It describes the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This is an adverb in German that means "gladly" or "with pleasure". It modifies the verb and indicates that the subject likes to perform the action described by the verb.</div><div><strong>allein</strong> This is an adjective used as an adverb in German, meaning "alone". It indicates the manner in which the traveling is done, specifying that it’s done without company.</div>','<h2>Sie kann sehr hoch springen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "she" in the nominative case, serving as the subject of the sentence. It can also mean "they" or be the formal "you" when capitalized, but the verb form here indicates it means "she".</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". This modal verb indicates ability or possibility.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It intensifies the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>hoch</strong> This is an adjective that means "high" in English. In this context, it is used as an adverb to describe the manner of the verb "springen".</div><div><strong>springen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb which means "to jump" in English. It’s the main action of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Sie hat einen neuen Laptop.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the indefinite article "ein", like "an" in English. It is used here because "Laptop" is a masculine noun and the object of the sentence is in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>neuen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular form of the adjective "neu", meaning "new". In German, adjectives change form to agree with the gender, case, and number of the nouns they describe.</div><div><strong>Laptop</strong> This is a masculine noun in German which has been borrowed from the English language, and it means the same -- "laptop" (computer).</div>','<h2>Sie wählt den grünen Stift.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, indicating the person performing the action.</div><div><strong>wählt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "wählen", which means "to choose" or "to select". It indicates the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine accusative definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to reference a specific, masculine noun in the accusative case, which is "Stift".</div><div><strong>grünen</strong> This is the masculine accusative form of the adjective "grün", which means "green" in English. In German, adjectives agree in gender, number, and case with the nouns they describe. Here, it is describing "Stift" and matches it in the masculine accusative form.</div><div><strong>Stift</strong> This is a masculine noun in German that means "pen" in English. It is the direct object of the sentence, meaning it is the thing being selected.</div>','<h2>Sie hat sich an etwas erinnert.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English, and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of "haben", which means "to have" in English. In this sentence, it is a helper verb used to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, which refers back to the subject of the sentence. It indicates that the action of the verb is done to oneself.</div><div><strong>an etwas</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "an" meaning "at" or "on" in English with the indefinite pronoun "etwas" meaning "something". Together, it can be translated as "to something" within this context.</div><div><strong>erinnert</strong> This is the past participle of "erinnern", which means "to remember" in English. It is used here in the perfect tense with "hat" to indicate a completed action, i.e., she has remembered something.</div>','<h2>Sie sah Vögel am Himmel.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sah</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". It indicates that the action of seeing took place in the past.</div><div><strong>Vögel</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Vogel", which means "bird" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, representing what she saw.</div><div><strong>am</strong> This is a contraction of "an dem" in German, which is a preposition followed by a definite article translating to "at the" or "on the" in English. It indicates the location where the birds were seen.</div><div><strong>Himmel</strong> This is the German word for "sky". It’s used here as a masculine singular noun denoting the location above the Earth where the birds were seen.</div>','<h2>Sie muss den Bericht schreiben.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. However, it can also mean "you" (formal, both singular and plural) in the nominative case. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>muss</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "to have to" or "must". It indicates obligation or necessity.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the definite article in the accusative case for masculine nouns in German. It is used here to mark the direct object of the sentence, "den Bericht".</div><div><strong>Bericht</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "report" in English. As the direct object of the verb "schreiben", it takes the accusative case.</div><div><strong>schreiben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to write". It is used here in conjunction with the modal verb "muss" to express that the subject must perform the action of writing.</div>','<h2>Sie hat eine schöne Stimme.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "she". It is the third-person singular nominative case and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or the existence of something.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, used for feminine and plural nouns in the accusative and nominative cases. It translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>schöne</strong> This is an adjective in German, which means "beautiful" or "nice". It agrees in gender (feminine), number (singular), and case (nominative/accusative) with the noun it describes. In this sentence, it is attributive, which means it is used in front of the noun.</div><div><strong>Stimme</strong> This is a feminine noun in the nominative case, which means "voice".</div>','<h2>Sie hat fünf Jahre lang getanzt.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it is used to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>fünf Jahre lang</strong> This phrase means "for five years" in English. "Fünf Jahre" refers to the duration of time, and "lang" is an adverb meaning "for (a duration)" to emphasize the period over which the action has been taking place.</div><div><strong>getanzt</strong> This is the past participle of "tanzen", which means "to dance". In the present perfect tense, it combines with the auxiliary verb "hat" to indicate that the action of dancing took place in the past over the mentioned period.</div>','<h2>Es regnet selten hier.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, often used with weather expressions.</div><div><strong>regnet</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "regnen", which means "to rain". It describes the action that is taking place.</div><div><strong>selten</strong> This is an adverb meaning "rarely" or "seldom". It modifies the verb "regnet" and indicates the infrequency of the action.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is an adverb meaning "here". It specifies the location where it "rarely rains".</div>','<h2>Es dauert zwischen drei und fünf Tagen.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dauert</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "dauern", which means "to last" or "to take (a period of time)". It indicates the duration of an action or event.</div><div><strong>zwischen</strong> This word translates to "between" in English. It’s a preposition used to indicate a range or an interval.</div><div><strong>drei</strong> This is the cardinal number "three" in German. It specifies the lower limit of the time range indicated in the sentence.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word means "and" in English. It is a conjunction used to link words or groups of words of the same type.</div><div><strong>fünf</strong> This is the cardinal number "five" in German. It specifies the upper limit of the time range indicated in the sentence.</div><div><strong>Tagen</strong> This is the dative plural form of the noun "Tag", which means "day". In this context, it indicates the unit of time over which the duration is being measured. Due to the preposition "zwischen", the noun appears in its dative plural form to indicate the time period within which something occurs.</div>','<h2>Es ist wichtig, dass du verstehst.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s used as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It connects the subject with the predicate adjective "wichtig".</div><div><strong>wichtig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "important". It’s used here to describe the importance of the ensuing clause.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "that". It introduces a subordinate clause which contains the important content to be understood.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>verstehst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "verstehen", which means "to understand". It indicates the action that the subject (du) is expected to perform within the context of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Sie können hier bleiben, es ist sehr spät.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for either singular or plural when addressing someone respectfully. It is also the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>können</strong> This is a modal verb in German, which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates possibility or ability.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "here". It indicates the location where the speaker suggests someone can stay.</div><div><strong>bleiben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to stay" in German. It’s used here in combination with the modal verb "können" to express "can stay".</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter pronoun "it" in German, often used as a subject for impersonal statements or for weather and time expressions.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "es" to the adjective "spät".</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in German. It’s used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>spät</strong> This is an adjective meaning "late" in German. In the sentence, it’s used to describe the time indicating it is very late.</div>','<h2>Es regnete draußen; allerdings hatten sie trotzdem eine gute Zeit.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun, functioning as a dummy subject similar to "it" in English when referring to the weather.</div><div><strong>regnete</strong> This is the past tense (Imperfekt) form of the verb "regnen" which means "to rain". It indicates that it was raining.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "outside", specifying the location of the rain. </div><div><strong>allerdings</strong> This is a German concessive adverb meaning "however" or "nonetheless". It introduces a contrast or concession in the sentence.</div><div><strong>hatten</strong> This is the past tense (Perfekt) form of the auxiliary verb "haben" which means "to have". It is used here to form the past perfect tense of the following verb "eine gute Zeit haben".</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the German third-person plural pronoun "they". It serves as the subject of the clause describing who had a good time.</div><div><strong>trotzdem</strong> A German adverb meaning "nevertheless" or "despite that"; indicating that something occurred or felt in spite of the circumstances mentioned before.</div><div><strong>eine gute Zeit</strong> This phrase means "a good time". "Eine" is the feminine indefinite article for "a", "gute" is the feminine singular form of "good", and "Zeit" meaning "time" is a feminine noun.</div>','<h2>Sie verlassen die Schule um halb vier.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "they" or the formal "you". In this sentence, it’s the subject and refers to either a group of people or a formally addressed individual.</div><div><strong>verlassen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "verlassen", which means "to leave". It indicates the action being taken by the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>die Schule</strong> This is a noun phrase where "die" is the definite article for feminine nouns in accusative case, and "Schule" means "school". It’s the object of the sentence, indicating the place being left.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a preposition that indicates a specific time in German. It translates to "at" in English when referring to time.</div><div><strong>halb vier</strong> This is a time expression in German that translates to "half past three" or "3:30" in English. The phrase "halb" means "half", which indicates a point in time half an hour before the full hour mentioned, in this case, "vier" (four).</div>','<h2>Sie werden einen neuen Welpen annehmen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "they" in the nominative case, or formal "you" when addressing someone respectfully. In this sentence, it is the subject.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the German auxiliary verb that forms the future tense. Here, it’s used to indicate that the action will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the German indefinite article in the accusative case for masculine nouns, which translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>neuen</strong> This is the German adjective for "new" in the accusative masculine singular form. German adjectives change their endings based on gender, number, and case of the nouns they describe.</div><div><strong>Welpen</strong> This is the German noun for "puppy" in the accusative singular. In this sentence, it is the direct object that is going to be adopted.</div><div><strong>annehmen</strong> This is the German separable verb meaning "to adopt" or "to accept". In the infinitive form here, it completes the future tense construction started by "werden".</div>','<h2>Sie sind bereit, ein neues Haus zu haben.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" or the formal "you". In this sentence, it can mean "they are" or "you are" (formal), depending on the context. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural or formal second person (singular and plural) present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here to express the state of being ready.</div><div><strong>bereit</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "ready". In this sentence, it’s used to suggest preparedness or willingness.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the German indefinite article for the nominative or accusative case, masculine or neuter, which translates as "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here to introduce "neues Haus", meaning "a new house".</div><div><strong>neues</strong> This is the German adjective meaning "new", agreeing in case, number, and gender with the noun "Haus". It’s in the nominative singular neuter form due to agreeing with "Haus".</div><div><strong>Haus</strong> This is a German noun meaning "house". It’s in the nominative case, as it is the thing that is to be had.</div><div><strong>zu haben</strong> This is an infinitive construction with "zu", which can be translated as "to have". It follows certain German adjectives and indicates the infinitive form of a verb, in this case "haben", which is the verb "to have" in English. The usage of "zu" before the infinitive is a common way to express purpose or intent in German.</div>','<h2>Sie gingen Kanufahren auf dem Fluss.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gingen</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". Here, it’s combined with "Kanufahren" to mean "went canoeing".</div><div><strong>Kanufahren</strong> This is a German noun in the infinitive form, used here as a part of a compound verb structure with "gingen" to describe the activity of canoeing.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition that can have several meanings depending on the context. Here, it’s used with the dative case and means "on" indicating the location where the canoeing took place.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is a definite article in the dative singular, which corresponds to "the" in English. It precedes the noun "Fluss" to indicate a specific river.</div><div><strong>Fluss</strong> This is a masculine singular noun that means "river" in English.</div>','<h2>Sie waren glücklich, die Show zu sehen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "they" or the formal "you". It’s used here as the subject of the sentence. In this context, it probably means "they" but could also be the formal "you" if it’s addressing someone directly.</div><div><strong>waren</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It indicates the past state of being of the subject. If "Sie" is used in the formal sense, then this form also serves as the formal "you" past tense.</div><div><strong>glücklich</strong> This German word is an adjective meaning "happy". In this sentence, it describes the emotional state of the subject, implying they were happy.</div><div><strong>die Show</strong> This is a German noun phrase meaning "the show". "Die" is the definite article for feminine nouns in the nominative and accusative case, and "Show" is a loanword from English, used here in the accusative case as the object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>zu sehen</strong> This verb phrase is an infinitive construction used with "zu" which translates to "to see" in English. It’s part of the infinitive phrase that explains the action related to being happy, which is seeing the show.</div>','<h2>Sie spielen mit gefälschten Pistolen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "they" or the formal "you" (singular or plural). In this sentence, it’s the subject.</div><div><strong>spielen</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". This form could also match the formal "you" as in "Sie spielen". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "with". It is used here to show the relationship between the action of playing and the objects involved.</div><div><strong>gefälschten</strong> This is the plural form of the past participle of "fälschen", which means "to forge" or "to fake", turned into an adjective. It is used here to describe the pistols as "forged" or "faked". It is declined in the dative plural because it is part of a prepositional phrase with "mit", which requires the dative case.</div><div><strong>Pistolen</strong> This is the plural form of "Pistole", the German word for "pistol". It is the direct object of the preposition "mit" and refers to what is being played with.</div>','<h2>Sie durften neue Kleider kaufen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" used as the subject of the sentence. It is also the formal "you" when used as a polite singular or plural form of address, but in this context, it’s "they".</div><div><strong>durften</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense of the modal verb "dürfen", which means "to be allowed to" or "may". It indicates permission or possibility in the past.</div><div><strong>neue</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "new". It is the accusative plural form, agreeing in case and number with the noun it describes, "Kleider".</div><div><strong>Kleider</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Kleid", meaning "dresses" or "clothes". Here it is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "kaufen".</div><div><strong>kaufen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to buy". In this sentence, it is used with the modal verb "durften" to express what they were allowed to do (buy new clothes).</div>','<h2>Sie sprachen über ihr Wochenende.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence. However, it can also be the formal second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you" when addressing someone respectfully.</div><div><strong>sprachen</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "sprechen", which means "to speak" or "to talk" in English. It indicates that the talking happened in the past.</div><div><strong>über</strong> This is a German preposition that means "about" or "over" in English. It is used here to introduce the topic of their conversation.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that can mean "her", "their", or "your" (formal) in English. It agrees with the gender and number of the possessor. In this sentence, since "Sie" is the subject, "ihr" likely refers to "their" weekend, but could also mean "your" in a formal context.</div><div><strong>Wochenende</strong> This is a German noun meaning "weekend" in English. It is in the accusative case because it is the object of the preposition "über".</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);